To ask form confirmation you can use the `confirm()` dialog. It&#39;s modal and will return `true` or `false` depending on the option the user clicked on.

Also note that you can make a couple of code improvements here. Firstly use a single delegated event handler instead of binding a new handler on every `li` you create. Secondly call `preventDefault()` on the `submit` event instead of returning `false`. Lastly, cache the `.input` selector instead of making a DOM request each time it&#39;s needed. Try this:

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    jQuery(function($) {
      $(&#39;ul&#39;).on(&#39;click&#39;, &#39;li&#39;, function() {
        if (confirm(&#39;Are you sure?&#39;)) {
          $(this).remove();
        }
      })

      var $input = $(&#39;.input&#39;);

      $(&#39;form&#39;).submit(function(e) {
        e.preventDefault();
        if ($input.val() !== &#39;&#39;) {
          var newTask = $(&#39;.input&#39;).val();
          $(&#39;ul&#39;).prepend(&#39;&lt;li&gt;&#39; + newTask + &#39;&lt;/li&gt;&#39;);
          $input.val(&#39;&#39;);
        }
      });

      $(&#39;ul&#39;).sortable();
    });

You can use the built-in [confirm()][1] which returns a boolean value.

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    $(document).ready(function($) {
      $(&#39;li&#39;).on(&#39;click&#39;, function() {
        if (confirm(&#39;Please confirm to delete&#39;)) {
          $(this).remove();
        }
      });
    });

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;script src=&quot;https://code.jquery.com/jquery-3.4.1.min.js&quot; integrity=&quot;sha256-CSXorXvZcTkaix6Yvo6HppcZGetbYMGWSFlBw8HfCJo=&quot; crossorigin=&quot;anonymous&quot;&gt;&lt;/script&gt;

    &lt;ul&gt;
      &lt;li&gt;Coffee&lt;/li&gt;
      &lt;li&gt;Tea&lt;/li&gt;
      &lt;li&gt;Milk&lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;


  [1]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Window/confirm

